article.headline: New Hampshire 81, Harvard 75
article.story: BOSTON (AP) -- Ronnie Dennis shot 6-of-8 from 3-point range and scored a career high 26 points to lead New Hampshire past Harvard 81-75 on Saturday afternoon. Last season New Hampshire (2-2) won just five games, and didn't pick up their second victory until January 8. The win also brought the Wildcats to .500 for just the second time since 1998. The program is coming off its seventh straight losing season. New Hampshire began the game with a 24-6 run, and led 65-47 with 7:40 left before Harvard (0-3) put a scare into the Wildcats by outscoring them 28-16 the rest of the way. The Crimson got as close as 79-75 on a pair of Kyle Rogus free throws with 25 seconds left, but the Wildcats stopped Harvard on their next possession and Luke McCrone hit two free throws to seal the victory for New Hampshire. New Hampshire shot 7-of-9 from 3-point range and 11-for-11 from the free throw line during the first half, and went on runs of 16-3 and 8-0 to take a 40-27 lead at halftime. Harvard's inexperience showed as the Crimson allowed New Hampshire to score 27 points off of turnovers. Rogus led Harvard with a career-high 27 points. Craig Walls added 14 points and 8 rebounds for the Wildcats, who shot 10-of-17 from 3-point range.
